Part 4

Reddy was waiting outside the Secretariat gate when Vikram's car pulled up. He was standing in the thin shade of a neem tree, a newspaper folded into thirds held loosely in one hand, the way you hold something when you have stopped expecting the car to arrive on time.

"You look well-rested," Reddy said by way of greeting. He adjusted his glasses, sounding almost suspicious of the fact.

"Ramanna's wedding," Vikram said, adjusting his collar. "His daughter's."

"Whose wedding?"

"It is a long story," Vikram said, opening the door of the administrative building.

Reddy studied him for a moment, decided not to pursue the matter, and turned toward the dark corridor of the entrance. "Don't expect the same kind of hospitality in here as you got in the village."

---

The Minister's outer office ran on its own private, glacial clock. 

Twenty minutes became forty, and forty slowly stretched into an hour. A peon brought two rounds of sweet tea in small glasses that nobody had asked for, while a queue of other petitioners came and went ahead of them with the easy confidence of people who had learned exactly which palms needed greasing and which doors required patience.

The peon — his name, Vikram read from the small laminated badge on his shirt, was Murthy — had been the one whose chai break had temporarily halted the office seal. He returned from it with a slightly defensive air, setting down the tea glasses and mentioning, to nobody in particular, that the canteen queue had been unusually long today because they were serving kesari bath, which is why it took so long, and by the way was there anything else required at this moment.

Nobody answered him.

He found something to do at the far end of the corridor and was gone again within four minutes.

"This is normal," Reddy said, not looking up from the legal files resting on his lap. "Don't take the delay personally."

"I'm not," Vikram said.

"You are checking your watch every four minutes," Reddy pointed out, his voice dry.

Vikram stopped checking his watch and rested his hands on the armrests of the vinyl chair.

---

Minister Satyanarayana, when they were finally shown in, turned out to be a small, unhurried man sitting behind a very large teak desk. He gestured for them to sit without getting up himself, and came to the point much faster than the long wait outside had suggested he would.

"Liquor," the Minister said, rolling the word on his tongue as if tasting it and not much liking it. "Do you know what that word does to my file in this state during an election year?"

"I understand it is politically sensitive, sir," Vikram said.

"Sensitive?" The Minister smiled, a dry expression that had no warmth in it. "My predecessor lost his assembly seat over a minor liquor policy change. Not because people stopped drinking. But because the opposition newspapers made him look like the man who let the poor family go hungry so he could line his pockets. It doesn't matter if it is true. It only has to be sayable."

Reddy leaned forward, his hands resting on the edge of the desk. "Sir, with respect, the industry exists whether or not our company enters the market. We are asking for a simple land allocation for a compliant, licensed unit. Nothing about the moral question changes because of who holds the license."

"Everything about the moral question changes based on whose name is printed on the license, Reddy garu," the Minister said, his voice dropping. "You know this game as well as I do. Your father's company is a big name. A big target, if the opposition wants to make an example of us."

"So the land is not available," Vikram said.

"I didn't say that," the Minister said, leaning back in his tall leather chair. "I said it is not available easily. There is a difference, and that difference costs time, not just money."

---

Outside, back in the car as it pulled into the heavy traffic of the main road, Reddy didn't bother softening the truth.

"This is exactly what I meant in the boardroom," Reddy said, looking out the side window. "This isn't home ground, Vikram. Here, every 'no' has to be understood as a 'maybe,' and every 'maybe' has to be earned twice over, because nobody down here owes your father's name anything yet."

"I heard you the first time. In the boardroom," Vikram said.

"Hearing and understanding are not the same thing," Reddy said, his tone firm but not unkind. "I'll be honest with you. I still don't know if this land allocation will come through in a month or in three years. It could go either way. It could not go at all."

Vikram looked out the window at the heavy iron gates of the Secretariat shrinking behind them in the dust. 

"Then we wait," Vikram said quietly. "And we don't waste the waiting."

Reddy glanced at him sideways, as if that sentence hadn't sounded quite like the Vikram he had expected to manage on this trip. He said nothing about it, filing the observation away the way careful men file things they intend to bring up again when the pressure rises.

[End of Part 4]
